    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output='Based on the provided excerpts from the SpaceX S-1 registration statement, here is a detailed breakdown of the lock-up agreements, restrictions on selling shares, dilution disclosures, and the price sensitivity table.\n\n### 1. Lock-Up Agreements and Periods\nThe S-1 outlines two primary lock-up periods restricting the sale, transfer, or hedging of shares post-IPO:\n\n*   **366-Day Lock-Up (Founder and Significant Investors):** The Founder (Elon Musk) and certain significant investors have agreed to a 366-day lock-up period. This covers an aggregate of [blank] shares, which includes **100% of the shares owned by the Founder**, representing [blank]% of total shares outstanding. \n    *   *No Early Release:* The total amount of shares subject to this 366-day lock-up will **not** be subject to any early release provisions. The Founder is explicitly not a party to any early release provisions during this extended lock-up period.\n*   **180-Day Lock-Up (Company, Directors, Officers, and Remaining Shareholders):** SpaceX, along with all of its directors, executive officers, and remaining shareholders, is subject to a 180-day lock-up period from the date of the prospectus.\n\n### 2. Restrictions on Selling Shares\nDuring their respective lock-up periods, restricted parties cannot engage in the following transactions without the prior written consent of Goldman Sachs & Co. LLC (on behalf of the underwriters), subject to certain exceptions:\n\n*   **Transfers and Dispositions:** Offering, selling, contracting to sell, pledging, granting options, lending, or otherwise transferring/disposing of common stock or securities convertible into common stock (collectively, "lock-up securities").\n*   **Hedging and Derivatives:** Engaging in any hedging or transaction (including short sales, puts, calls, forwards, swaps, or other derivatives) designed to or reasonably expected to result in a sale or transfer of the economic consequences of ownership of the lock-up securities.\n*   **Registration Demands:** Making any demand for or exercising any right with respect to the registration of lock-up securities.\n*   **Public Announcements:** Publicly announcing any intention to engage in any of the prohibited actions above.\n\n**Exceptions and Early Release Provisions:**\n*   **M&A Exception:** The restrictions do not apply to securities issued by SpaceX in connection with mergers, acquisitions, or similar transactions during the lock-up period.\n*   **Directed Share Program:** Shares purchased by certain employees, management associates, friends, and family through the directed share program are **not** subject to lock-up restrictions.\n*   **Staggered Early Release (for 180-day and a portion of 366-day shares):** Automatic releases from restrictions apply earlier than 180 days for "Early Release Eligible Shares" based on the following schedule:\n    *   **Up to 20%** released on or after the second full trading day following the public release of quarterly financial results for the quarter ended June 30, 2026 (the "First Earnings Release Date").\n    *   **Up to an additional 10%** released if the closing price on Nasdaq is at least 30% greater than the IPO price for at least five of the ten consecutive trading days ending on the First Earnings Release Date.\n    *   **Up to an additional 7%** released on or after each of the dates that are 70, 90, 105, 120, and 135 days after the offering.\n    *   **Up to an additional 28%** released following the public release of quarterly financial results for the quarter ended September 30, 2026.\n    *   **All remaining shares** released on or after 180 days post-offering.\n\n**Post-Lock-Up Status:** \nOnce lock-up agreements expire, shares held by Mr. Musk and other existing investors (currently deemed "restricted securities") will be eligible for sale in the public market under Rule 144 or Rule 701 exemptions, subject to affiliate limitations. Holders of approximately [blank] Class A common shares also have registration rights under an Investors\' Rights Agreement.\n\n### 3. Dilution Disclosures\nPurchasers of Class A common stock in the IPO will experience "immediate and substantial dilution" in net tangible book value per share. \n\n*   **Pre-IPO Net Tangible Book Value:** As of March 31, 2026, SpaceX\'s net tangible book value was approximately $[blank], or $[blank] per share of Class A common stock.\n*   **Post-IPO Adjusted Pro Forma Net Tangible Book Value:** After giving effect to the sale of shares in the offering, underwriting discounts, estimated expenses, the Class C Reclassification, and the Preferred Conversion, the adjusted pro forma net tangible book value as of March 31, 2026, would be approximately $[blank], or $[blank] per share.\n*   **Impact on Existing Investors:** This represents an immediate decrease in net tangible book value of $[blank] per share to Mr. Musk and other existing investors.\n*   **Impact on New Investors:** New investors will face immediate dilution equal to the difference between the initial public offering price and the adjusted pro forma net tangible book value per share—amounting to $[blank] per share.\n\n**Dilution Table:**\nThe S-1 includes the following table to illustrate this per-share dilution:\n*   Initial public offering price per share: **$[blank]**\n*   Pro forma net tangible book value per share as of March 31, 2026: **$[blank]**\n*   Decrease per share attributable to new investors in this offering: **[blank]**\n*   As adjusted pro forma net tangible book value per share after giving further effect to this offering: **[blank]**\n*   Dilution in pro forma net tangible book value per share to new investors in this offering: **$[blank]**\n\nThe filing also notes a comparison table will be provided showing the total consideration paid and the average price per share paid by Mr. Musk/existing investors versus new investors.\n\n### 4. Price Sensitivity Table\nThe S-1 provides a sensitivity analysis illustrating how fluctuations in the IPO price or the number of shares offered would impact the dilution to new investors:\n\n*   **Price Sensitivity:** If the initial public offering price were to increase or decrease by **$1.00 per share**, the dilution in pro forma net tangible book value per share of Class A common stock to new investors would equal **$[blank]** or **$[blank]**, respectively.\n*   **Share Count Sensitivity:** If the number of shares of Class A common stock offered by SpaceX were to increase or decrease by **[blank] shares**, the dilution in pro forma net tangible book value per share to new investors would be **$[blank]** or **$[blank]**, respectively.',
