        output='Based on the provided S-1 preamble sections, here are the details regarding the Qualified IPO, conversion of preferred stock, dual-class voting structure, post-IPO capitalization, and equity classification:\n\n### 1. Qualified IPO Thresholds and Conditions\nThe SpaceX Redeemable Convertible Preferred Stock is subject to automatic conversion upon the occurrence of a "Qualified IPO" or a specified holder consent date. \n*   **Qualified IPO Definition:** A Qualified IPO is defined as the Company’s sale of its common stock in a public offering pursuant to a registration statement under the Securities Act of 1933.\n*   **Thresholds:** The offering must meet two specific financial thresholds:\n    1.  The **pre-public offering market capitalization** of the Company must be at least **$6.0 billion**.\n    2.  The offering must result in **aggregate cash proceeds** to the Company of not less than **$250 million**.\n*   **Alternative Condition:** The preferred stock will also automatically convert on the date specified by written consent or agreement of the applicable holders of the preferred stock, voting in accordance with their series.\n\n### 2. Conversion of Preferred Stock\n*   **Conversion Rate:** The conversion rate is determined by dividing the initial price by the conversion price. Following the 2026 Stock Split, each share of SpaceX Redeemable Convertible Preferred Stock is convertible into **fifty shares** of SpaceX Common Stock. The conversion price is subject to standard adjustments for dilutive issuances, splits, and combinations.\n*   **Class Conversion Mechanics:** \n    *   Holders of Series A and Series B preferred stock can convert at any time into Class A, Class B, or Class C Common Stock. \n    *   Holders of all other series of preferred stock can convert at any time into Class A or Class C Common Stock.\n    *   *Historical Restriction:* Prior to SpaceX’s conversion to a Texas entity, Series A and Series B holders were only permitted to convert to Class B Common Stock, and other series holders were restricted to Class A Common Stock.\n*   **Transfer-Triggered Cancellation:** If a share of Series A or Series B is transferred (other than a "Permitted Transfer" as defined in the charter), it will automatically be cancelled and converted into a corresponding share of Series A-1 or Series B-1.\n\n### 3. Dual-Class Voting Structure\nSpaceX utilizes a multi-class voting structure designed to concentrate voting control with Elon Musk and other holders of Class B common stock.\n*   **Class A Common Stock:** Entitles holders to **one vote** per share.\n*   **Class B Common Stock:** Entitles holders to **ten votes** per share. \n*   **Class C Common Stock:** Holders have **no voting rights**, except as required by law.\n*   **Class D Common Stock:** Voting rights will be established by the Board of Directors if and when any shares are issued.\n*   **Board Control:** Class A and Class B shareholders vote together as a single class on most matters. However, Class B shareholders, voting separately as a class, have the right to elect **51%** (a majority) of the total number of authorized directors.\n*   **Preferred Stock Voting:** Holders of Series A and Series B preferred stock have **10 votes** for each share of Class B into which such share is convertible. Holders of all other series of preferred stock have **1 vote** for each share of Class A into which such share is convertible.\n*   **Class B Conversion:** Each share of Class B is convertible into one share of Class A at the option of the holder. It will also automatically convert into one share of Class A upon a transfer (except for Permitted Transfers).\n\n### 4. Post-IPO Capitalization\n*   **Authorized Shares (Post-IPO):** Upon completion of the offering, authorized capital stock will consist of:\n    *   **Class A:** 36,132,150,000 shares (par value $0.001)\n    *   **Class B:** 6,125,000,000 shares (par value $0.001)\n    *   **Class C:** 10,000,000,000 shares (par value $0.001)\n    *   **Preferred Stock:** 2,400,000,000 shares (par value $0.001)\n*   **2026 Stock Split:** In May 2026, the Board approved a 2026 Stock Split, whereby each outstanding share of Class A, Class B, and Class C Common Stock was split into five shares of the same class.\n*   **Reserved Unissued Shares:** The Company is required to reserve sufficient unissued common stock to effect the conversion of all outstanding preferred stock and Class B stock, plus shares granted/available for equity grants. As of March 31, 2026, the reserved shares totaled:\n    *   Class A: 9,350 million shares\n    *   Class B: 3,725 million shares\n    *   Class C: 7,627 million shares\n*   **Pro Forma Assumptions:** The prospectus assumes the completion of a "Class C Reclassification" (reclassifying all Class C shares into Class A) and the "Preferred Conversion" (conversion of all preferred stock into Class A and Class B common stock) prior to the completion of the IPO.\n\n### 5. Classification Outside Permanent Equity\nThe SpaceX Redeemable Convertible Preferred Stock is presented outside of permanent equity on the Company\'s consolidated balance sheets as "Redeemable convertible preferred stock." \n*   **Reasoning:** The liquidation preference provisions are considered **contingent redemption provisions**. Because deemed liquidation events (such as a change of control) are not solely within the control of the Company, the preferred stock fails to meet the criteria for permanent equity classification.',
