be freely tradable without restriction under the Securities Act (unless held by "affiliates" as defined in Rule 144).\n- **All shares of Class A and Class B common stock issued prior to closing** — including those held by Elon Musk and other existing investors — are "restricted securities" under Rule 144, eligible for public sale only if registered or qualifying for a Rule 144 or Rule 701 exemption.\n- **Lock-up agreements** restrict a substantial number of shares from immediate resale, with **[blank]** shares (and potentially an additional **[blank]** shares assuming 100% conversion of Class B to Class A) becoming eligible for sale upon lock-up expiration.\n- **Registration rights** under the Investors\' Rights Agreement give certain existing shareholders the right to demand registration of approximately **[blank]** shares and to participate in future registrations, which could increase the float over time.\n- Approximately **[blank]** shares will generally become available for resale under Rule 144 starting **90 days** after the offering, subject to lock-up restrictions.\n\n---\n\n## Listing on Nasdaq\n\nSpaceX has applied to list its Class A common stock on **The Nasdaq Stock Market LLC ("Nasdaq")** and **Nasdaq Texas, Inc. ("Nasdaq Texas")** under the trading symbol **"SPCX."** This listing application is referenced repeatedly throughout the preamble.\n\nThe company will be a **"controlled company"** under Nasdaq and Nasdaq Texas listing rules because Mr. Musk will beneficially own a majority of the voting power. As a controlled company, SpaceX qualifies for and intends to rely on exemptions from certain corporate governance requirements — specifically, it will not be required to have a majority-independent board or independent compensation and nominating committees. However, it will remain subject to the requirement for an entirely independent audit committee.\n\nThe dual-class structure underpinning the listing is as follows:\n\n| Feature | Class A | Class B |\n|---|---|---|\n| Votes per share | 1 | 10 |\n| Conversion | N/A | Convertible to Class A at holder option or upon transfer (other than a Permitted Transfer) |\n| Board election rights | Vote together with Class B on all matters | Entitled to elect a majority of the board for so long as any Class B shares remain outstanding |\n\n---\n\n## Selling Stockholders\n\nThe S-1 preamble indicates that **this is an initial public offering of shares of Class A common stock offered by the company itself** — there are **no selling stockholders** participating in this offering. The cover page summary table confirms that the shares offered are "Class A common stock offered by us," and the underwriters\' over-allotment option is to purchase additional shares "from us."\n\nHowever, the document provides significant context about existing shareholders and their potential future impact on the public market:\n\n- **Mr. Musk** will beneficially own **[blank]** shares of Class A and **[blank]** shares of Class B common stock immediately after the offering, comprising approximately **[blank]%** of Class B common stock. Through his Class B holdings, he will control the majority of voting power and the ability to elect, remove, or fill vacancies among the Class B Directors.\n- **Other existing investors** hold restricted securities that were issued in private transactions.\n- Parties to the **Investors\' Rights Agreement** hold registration rights for approximately **[blank]** shares, which could lead to future registered resale offerings.\n- The underwriters have indicated they do not intend sales to discretionary accounts to exceed **5%** of the total shares offered.\n- Retail investor allocations are anticipated through specific online brokerage platforms: **Charles Schwab, Fidelity Brokerage Services/Fidelity Capital Markets, Robinhood Financial, SoFi Securities**, and **E*TRADE by Morgan Stanley** (an affiliate of underwriter Morgan Stanley & Co. LLC), all as selling group members. Purchases through these platforms will be at the same IPO price and timing as institutional purchases.\n\n---\n\n## Summary\n\nIn essence, the SpaceX S-1 preamble describes a **primary-only IPO** (no selling stockholders) with proceeds directed toward AI compute, launch infrastructure, satellite constellations, and general corporate purposes. The stock will list on Nasdaq and Nasdaq Texas under **"SPCX"** with a dual-class voting structure that maintains Mr. Musk\'s control, qualifying SpaceX as a controlled company. Existing shareholders\' shares remain restricted and locked up post-IPO, though registration rights and Rule 144 eligibility will gradually introduce additional shares into the public market.',
