    ),
    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output='# SpaceX S-1: Directed Share Program, Retail Allocations, and Discretionary Account Restrictions\n\n## Directed Share Program (DSP)\n\nThe S-1 establishes a **directed share program** administered by **Morgan Stanley & Co. LLC** (an underwriter in the offering) and its affiliates, described as a "global directed share program." Key terms include:\n\n- **Reservation size**: At the company\'s request, the underwriters reserved a specified percentage (left blank in the preliminary filing) of the Class A common stock shares to be issued and offered by the prospectus.\n- **Eligible participants**: Shares are offered at the IPO price to **employees of the Company and certain other designated individuals**.\n- **No lock-up**: Shares purchased through the DSP **will not be subject to a lock-up restriction**, unlike most IPO shares.\n- **Impact on public float**: The number of shares available for sale to the general public is **reduced** by the number of reserved shares sold to these persons.\n- **Unsold shares**: Any reserved shares not purchased by DSP participants will be **offered by the underwriters to the general public** on the same basis as other shares in the offering.\n- **Indemnification**: SpaceX agreed to indemnify the underwriters and their affiliates against certain liabilities and expenses, including Securities Act liabilities, in connection with sales of shares reserved for the DSP.\n- **Beneficial ownership table exclusion**: The beneficial ownership table explicitly **does not reflect** any shares purchasable through the DSP.\n\n## Online Brokerage Platforms and Retail Investor Allocations\n\nBeyond allocations made to retail investors directly by the underwriters, SpaceX requested that certain shares be offered to retail investors through specific **selling group members** via their online brokerage platforms:\n\n| Platform | Role / Affiliation |\n|---|---|\n| **Charles Schwab & Co., Inc.** | Selling group member |\n| **Fidelity Brokerage Services LLC and Fidelity Capital Markets** (division of National Financial Services LLC) | Selling group member |\n| **Robinhood Financial, LLC** | Selling group member |\n| **SoFi Securities LLC** | Selling group member |\n| **E*TRADE by Morgan Stanley** | Affiliate of Morgan Stanley & Co. LLC (underwriter) |\n\nKey terms governing these retail allocations:\n\n- **No affiliation with SpaceX**: The platforms are explicitly stated as **not affiliated** with the company.\n- **Platform-specific terms**: Purchases are subject to the **terms, conditions, and requirements set by each selling group member**.\n- **Price and timing parity**: Any purchase through these platforms will be at the **same IPO price** and at the **same time** as any other purchases in the offering, including those by institutions and other large investors.\n\n## Restrictions on Discretionary Accounts\n\nThe underwriters informed SpaceX that **they do not intend sales to discretionary accounts to exceed 5%** of the total number of shares of Class A common stock offered by them. This is a standard IPO guardrail limiting the discretion underwriters have to allocate shares into accounts where the account holder has not specifically directed the purchase.\n\n## Nasdaq Listing\n\nSpaceX applied to list its Class A common stock on **Nasdaq** and **Nasdaq Texas** under the trading symbol **"SPCX."**\n\n## Summary of Allocation Architecture\n\nThe offering\'s retail allocation framework thus operates through **three parallel channels**:\n\n1. **Underwriter-directed retail allocations** — traditional institutional and retail distribution by the underwriting syndicate.\n2. **Online brokerage platform sales** — shares offered at SpaceX\'s request through five named platforms (Schwab, Fidelity, Robinhood, SoFi, E*TRADE), all at the same price and time as institutional purchases.\n3. **Directed Share Program** — a reserved percentage of shares for employees and designated individuals, administered by Morgan Stanley, with no lock-up, and with unsold balances reverting to the general public offering pool.\n\nAll three channels are constrained by the **5% discretionary account cap**, and the DSP and platform sales are explicitly designed to **reduce** the shares otherwise available to the general public only to the extent those reserved shares are actually purchased.',
